# Hotwire and Stimulus (Rails)

Full code examples and longer snippets live in `.cursor/rules/hotwire.md`. This file is the concise checklist for generation and review.

## Turbo Morphing

- Enable globally when needed: `turbo_refreshes_with method: :morph, scroll: :preserve`.
- Listen for `turbo:morph-element` to restore client-side state (timers, UI).
- Use `data-turbo-permanent` for elements that must survive morphs.
- Keep DOM `id` values unique; duplicates break morphing.
- For frames with `src`, use `refresh: :morph` (or `refresh: "morph"`) so the frame is not torn out during page morphs.

## Turbo Frames

- Wrap independent form sections in frames so partial responses do not reset everything.
- Heavy content: `loading: "lazy"` on the frame.
- Prefer in-place updates via `turbo_stream.replace` / stream responses instead of unnecessary redirects.
- `data-turbo-frame="_parent"` targets the parent frame without hard-coding the parent id.

### Broadcast streams and DOM

- The first argument to `broadcast_*_to` is the **subscription name** (channel); it does not have to match a `turbo-frame` id.
- `target:` is the **element id** in the page. One `turbo_stream_from` can drive multiple `target`s on the same stream.
- To update only frame contents: `broadcast_update_to` + a partial **without** a `<turbo-frame>` wrapper; the wrapper stays in the parent view.
- To replace the whole node: `broadcast_replace_to` — the rendered fragment must supply a valid root (often the same frame id for follow-up updates).

## Common issues

| Symptom | Fix direction |
|--------|----------------|
| Timers break after morph | Subscribe to `turbo:morph-element` |
| Form resets | Turbo Frame around the section |
| Pagination breaks | Unique ids |
| Flicker on replace | `method: :morph` on the stream |
| localStorage / drafts | Restore on `turbo:morph-element`; use `nextFrame()` if needed |

## Stimulus

- Prefer the **Values API** over manual `getAttribute` — clearer types and contract.
- Use **camelCase** in JS; `data-*-value` in markup follows Stimulus conventions.
- In **`disconnect()`**, clear timers, `removeEventListener`, `IntersectionObserver.disconnect`, etc.
- Scope actions with `:self` in `data-action` when appropriate.
- Shared logic belongs in modules (`debounce`, `throttle`, `nextFrame`, …), not duplicated per controller.

### Timers

```javascript
// Pattern: private field + clear in disconnect()
#timer
connect() { this.#timer = setInterval(...) }
disconnect() { clearInterval(this.#timer) }
```

## State and morph

- UI prefs and drafts: localStorage; a brief flash of default UI on first paint is acceptable.
- After morph, re-read storage; use `await nextFrame()` before applying to the DOM when needed.

## Links instead of JS-only buttons

- Filters and navigation: prefer plain `<a href>` for context menu, new tab, and predictable browser behavior.

## Turbo Streams + morph

For `turbo_stream.replace` on content that includes frames, pass `method: :morph` to reduce flicker. Mark nested frames `data-turbo-permanent` when required.

## Morph events on elements

Prefer `turbo:morph-element` on a specific element via `data-action` over a global `@window` listener when performance matters.

## UI toggles via POST

Toggles (watch, expand, etc.) should use **POST** (`data-turbo-method="post"`) with a Turbo Stream response — not GET with side effects.

## Models and broadcasting

- Use `broadcasts_refreshes` / `broadcast_*_to` as the scenario requires; templates subscribe with `turbo_stream_from` using the **same stream identifier**.
- Do not conflate concepts: stream name ≠ `turbo-frame` id.

## Forms: auto-submit / auto-save

- Auto-submit on `connect`: single `turbo:submit-end` listener, `requestSubmit`, `aria-busy`.
- Auto-save: debounce; on `disconnect`, final submit if the form is dirty; watch `#timer` and races.

## Dialogs

- `aria-hidden`, `showModal` / `show`, close on outside click; for open dialogs during morph, `preventDefault` when the event detail would drop `open`.
- On open, set lazy frames to `loading = "eager"` when needed.

## Fragment cache and personalization

If the cache cannot see `Current.user`, expose flags in `data-*` and style via Stimulus (`itemTargetConnected`, etc.); optional `meta name="current-user-id"` in the layout.

## Tests (turbo-rails)

Use `assert_turbo_frame`, `assert_no_turbo_frame`, and blocks with `assert_select` inside a frame — see turbo-rails docs.

## Flash via Turbo Stream

Extract a concern/helper such as `turbo_stream_flash`, render `replace` on a `#flash` container alongside other actions in `render turbo_stream: [...]`.

## Drag and drop

- Prefer a small Stimulus controller over heavy libraries when enough.
- `await nextFrame()` before applying classes in `dragstart`; track source container; after a successful drop, remove the node optimistically or wait for the server response.
- Accessibility: drag handle with `visually-hidden` copy; set `draggable` from the server with a flag.

## @rails/request.js

For consistency with Turbo: `window.fetch = Turbo.fetch` in `application.js` (if you follow that guide pattern).

## Progressive UI enablement

Hide the widget until `connect`, add an `installed` class in `connect`; after morph, wire `data-action` with `turbo:morph@document->...#install` if needed.

## Guiding principle

Less imperative JS where Turbo suffices (navigation, frames, streams). Stimulus is for per-element behavior, lifecycle, and DOM wiring; always clean up in `disconnect`.
